["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de Sefton was born about 1230, in Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Gilbert de Sotheworth. She died in 1270, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41, and was buried in Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1230–1270":"umbes 1230–1270","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1230–1270":"1230–1270","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Southworth Hall, Sourthworth With Croft, Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Croft with Southworth, Lancashire, England","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Croft with Southworth, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Croft with Southworth, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1230–1270":"noin 1230–1270","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1230–1270":"1230–1270","about 1250":"noin 1250","1300":"1300","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1329":"1329","about 1230":"noin 1230","Southworth Hall, Sourthworth With Croft, Warrington, Lancashire, England":"Croft with Southworth, Lancashire, England","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuninga